---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en" class="bg-gruvbox-bg0">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={`About - ${SITE_TITLE}`} description="About Amir and his technical journey" />
	</head>
	<body class="bg-gruvbox-bg0 text-gruvbox-fg1 min-h-screen">
		<Header />
		<main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
			<article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
				<header class="text-center mb-12">
					<h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gruvbox-fg0 mb-4">About Me</h1>
					<div class="w-16 h-1 bg-gruvbox-yellow mx-auto"></div>
				</header>
				
				<div class="space-y-6 text-gruvbox-fg2 leading-relaxed">
					<p class="text-xl text-gruvbox-fg1 font-medium">
						I'm Amir, a technologist passionate about the fundamentals of computing and the craft of programming.
					</p>

					<p>
						My journey in technology is driven by curiosity about how things work at the deepest levels. 
						I'm particularly drawn to <span class="text-gruvbox-green font-medium">low-level programming</span>, 
						<span class="text-gruvbox-blue font-medium">systems design</span>, and 
						<span class="text-gruvbox-purple font-medium">embedded development</span>. 
						I believe that understanding the underlying mechanisms makes you a better programmer, 
						regardless of what layer you're working at.
					</p>

					<p>
						I'm a strong advocate for <span class="text-gruvbox-orange font-medium">tool mastery</span> 
						and deliberate practice. In a world of endless frameworks and abstractions, I prefer to focus 
						on timeless fundamentals that will remain relevant for decades. This means diving deep into 
						topics like computer architecture, operating systems, compilers, and algorithms.
					</p>

					<p>
						My technical interests span several areas:
					</p>

					<div class="bg-gruvbox-bg1 border border-gruvbox-bg3 rounded-lg p-6 my-8">
						<div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
							<div>
								<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gruvbox-yellow mb-3">Programming & Languages</h3>
								<ul class="space-y-1 text-gruvbox-fg3">
									<li>• Language design and implementation</li>
									<li>• Compiler construction</li>
									<li>• Type systems and formal methods</li>
									<li>• Performance optimization</li>
								</ul>
							</div>
							<div>
								<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gruvbox-blue mb-3">Systems & Architecture</h3>
								<ul class="space-y-1 text-gruvbox-fg3">
									<li>• Operating systems internals</li>
									<li>• Computer architecture</li>
									<li>• Network programming</li>
									<li>• Distributed systems</li>
								</ul>
							</div>
							<div>
								<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gruvbox-purple mb-3">Embedded & Hardware</h3>
								<ul class="space-y-1 text-gruvbox-fg3">
									<li>• Microcontroller programming</li>
									<li>• Real-time systems</li>
									<li>• Hardware interfacing</li>
									<li>• Signal processing</li>
								</ul>
							</div>
							<div>
								<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gruvbox-green mb-3">Tools & Philosophy</h3>
								<ul class="space-y-1 text-gruvbox-fg3">
									<li>• Linux and Unix philosophy</li>
									<li>• Text editors (Emacs enthusiast)</li>
									<li>• Build systems and automation</li>
									<li>• Open-source development</li>
								</ul>
							</div>
						</div>
					</div>

					<p>
						I'm somewhat contrarian when it comes to modern development practices. While others chase 
						the latest JavaScript framework, I'm more interested in understanding why certain design 
						decisions were made and what trade-offs they involve. I believe in choosing tools based 
						on technical merit rather than popularity.
					</p>

					<p>
						This blog serves multiple purposes: it's a way to document my learning journey, share 
						knowledge with others who are interested in similar topics, and contribute to the broader 
						conversation about software quality and engineering practices. I try to write posts that 
						are both technically rigorous and accessible to those willing to dig deeper.
					</p>

					<p>
						When I'm not writing code or blog posts, you might find me tinkering with hardware projects, 
						reading academic papers, or exploring the intersection of technology and philosophy. 
						I'm particularly interested in how the tools we use shape the way we think about problems.
					</p>

					<p class="text-gruvbox-fg1 font-medium">
						If you share similar interests or want to discuss any of the topics I write about, 
						feel free to reach out through the links in the footer. I'm always happy to connect 
						with fellow practitioners who value depth over breadth.
					</p>
				</div>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>